{"formerly":"","seq":"1,2,5,10,20,50,100,200,500,1000,2000,5000,10000,20000,50000,100000,200000,500000,1000000,2000000,5000000,10000000,20000000,50000000,100000000,200000000,500000000,1000000000,2000000000,5000000000","description":"Hyperinflation sequence for banknotes.","comments":"Denominations of Polish banknotes circa 1995.English coins in 2006 have denominations of 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200 pence.","formula":"a(3n)=10^n, a(3n+1)=2*10^n, a(3n+2)=5*10^na(n) = [(n%3)^2 + 1]*10^floor(n/3). E.g. a(0) = [(0%3)^2 + 1]*10^floor(0/3) = [0^2 + 1]*10^0 = 1, a(4) = [(4%3)^2 + 1]*10^floor(4/3) = [1^2 + 1]*10^1 = 20, a(8) = [(8%3)^2 + 1]*10^floor(8/3) = [2^2 + 1]*10^2 = 500. - Justin L. Brown (jlbrown(AT)neo.tamu.edu), Jun 17 2004G.f.: (1+2*x+5*x^2)/(1-10*x^3). - _Philippe Deléham_, Apr 08 2013a(n) = 10*a(n-3) with n>2, a(0)=1, a(1)=2, a(2)=5. - _Philippe Deléham_, Apr 08 2013","prog":"(Python) print( [ ((n % 3) ** 2 + 1) * 10**int(n/3) for n in range(100)] )","crossrefs":["Cf. A117727."],"keyword":"easy,nonn","offset":"0,2","author":"Robert Lozyniak (11(AT)onna.com)","extensions":["Second formula corrected by _Peter C. Lauterbach_, Nov 12 2010"]}